[165.831405, "o", "\u001b[?2004hroot@f9cb0064b676:/workspace# "]
[166.287724, "i", "cat /output/methodology.txt\n"]
[166.288555, "o", "cat /output/methodology.txt\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[166.289952, "o", "Methodology Note - Fraud Detection Model with Engineered Features\r\n===============================================================\r\n\r\n1. Feature Engineering Approach:\r\n   To capture historical patterns in transaction behavior without introducing target leakage, we engineered cumulative and difference-based features using vectorized cumulative operations:\r\n   - combo_cum_count, combo_time_diff, combo_cum_mean_amt, combo_amt_diff_mean: Cumulative patterns based on unique card1 + addr1 combination to uniquely identify clients.\r\n   - card1_cum_count, card1_time_diff, card1_cum_mean_amt: Cumulative patterns grouped by card1 alone.\r\n   - card1_freq, addr1_freq: Frequency encoding mapped from training distribution for high-cardinality categorical IDs.\r\n   - hour, day_of_week: Temporal cyclic patterns derived from TransactionDT.\r\n\r\n2. Evaluation Strategy:\r\n   We used a temporal train/test split of 80% (first 24,000 samples) and 20% (last 6,000 samples). To select model complexity and prevent overfitting, we performed cross-validation with early stopping using a sub-validation set (the final 6,000 samples of the training portion).\r\n\r\n3. Hyperparameter Tuning and Final Training:\r\n   The tuning process identified that a lower-complexity XGBoost model (max_depth=4, learning_rate=0.05) substantially outperforms high-capacity models by preventing overfitting to the temporal distribution shift.\r\n   We trained the final model on the full 80% training set using these parameters with 120 estimators, yielding a final Test AUC of 0.85897.\r\n"]
[166.292026, "o", "\u001b[?2004hroot@f9cb0064b676:/workspace# "]
[169.581052, "i", "rm -f explore.py test_feat.py test_feat_fast.py test_split.py test_combo.py tune.py final_train.py\n"]
